<refnamediv><refname>imbinarize</refname><refpurpose>Convert an image to a boolean mask using fixed or automatic thresholding.</refpurpose></refnamediv>
<refsynopsisdiv><title>Syntax</title><synopsis>[bw, level] = imbinarize(image)
[bw, level] = imbinarize(image, method)</synopsis></refsynopsisdiv>
<refsection><title>Parameters</title><variablelist>
<varlistentry><term>image</term><listitem><para>A grayscale or RGB image.</para></listitem></varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term>method</term><listitem><para><literal>global</literal>, <literal>otsu</literal>, <literal>triangle</literal>, or a normalized scalar threshold. The default is <literal>otsu</literal>.</para></listitem></varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term>bw</term><listitem><para>A boolean mask.</para></listitem></varlistentry>
<varlistentry><term>level</term><listitem><para>The normalized threshold used.</para></listitem></varlistentry>
</variablelist></refsection>
<refsection><title>Description</title><para><function>imbinarize</function> is the mask-oriented convenience API. It applies fixed, Otsu, or Triangle thresholding through <function>imthreshold</function> and always returns a boolean image. Use <function>imthreshold</function> when a numeric uint8 result or modes such as <literal>trunc</literal> and <literal>tozero</literal> are required.</para></refsection>
<refsection><title>Examples</title><programlisting><![CDATA[
image = imread(fullpath(getIPCVpath() + "/images/coins_gray.jpg"));
[bw, level] = imbinarize(image, "global");
imshow(bw);
]]></programlisting></refsection>
